==Annotations==
'''''absit nomen'''''{{spaces|5}}(''Latin'') ''let the name be absent''.<ref>Gifford (1988) 207.</ref> Stephen is alluding to the Latin precept ''absit nomen, absit omen'' (''If you do not utter an ill-omened expression, you will not incur the bad luck attendant on it''). The second half of this phrase, ''absit omen'' (''let there be no [ill] omen''), is used on its own as an [[wikt:apotropaic|apotropaic]] phrase to ward off any possible bad luck that might attend the uttering of an ill-omened term; today one might knock on wood to achieve the same effect.<ref>{{cite book |title=Slang and Euphemism |last=Spears |first=Richard A. |year=1981 |publisher=Jonathan David Publishers, Inc. |location=New York |isbn=0-8246-0273-0}}</ref> 


