{{BookCat}}

[[File:Ulysses, 1922.djvu|thumb|600px|center|page=313]]
<br>
==Annotations==
'''Decree ''nisi'''''{{spaces|5}}(''Latin'') A [[w:Decree nisi|legal term]] from the Latin ''[[wikt:decree nisi|nisi]]'' (''unless''), denoting a court order that will become [[wikt:decree absolute|absolute]] at a specified date unless cause can be shown why it should not.<ref>Gifford (1988) 348.</ref> In British law the term is most commonly applied to the initial stage of divorce proceedings, the divorce becoming absolute six months later. J. J. O'Molloy, a solicitor, is jocosely suggesting that the adultery of [[w:Derbforgaill|Derbforgaill]] and her paramour [[w:Diarmait Mac Murchada|Diarmait Mac Murchada]] might have been used by her husband [[w:Tigernán Us Ruairc|Tigernán Us Ruairc]] as grounds for a divorce.

